prompts.copyContent:
INSTALL OR REPAIR EXECUTABLE EVALS FOR THE TARGET SKILL NOW. DO NOT RETURN ONLY A RUBRIC, TEST PLAN, EXAMPLE PROMPTS, OR PERFORMANCE ADVICE.

Repo: resolve the current repository from the environment.
Branch: preserve existing work and use an isolated branch or worktree.
Target skill: xyz_skill_id_or_path
Sprint: Skill Correctness, Weakness, and Efficiency Evaluation.
Owned scope: the target skill's eval cases, fixtures, runner, result schema, scoring contract, performance and token instrumentation, focused CI, and directly related skill, trigger, capability, or factoring repairs.
Forbidden scope: unrelated skills, production deployment, provider credentials, hidden benchmark data, destructive cleanup, force-push, validator weakening, metric gaming, and unbounded prompt rewriting.
Expected artifacts: tracked eval contract, executable runner, versioned cases and fixtures, machine-readable results, before/after correctness and efficiency evidence, focused CI, commit SHA, and push or PR evidence.

MISSION
Build an eval system that does more than confirm the skill can run. It must identify bugs, inefficiencies, routing mistakes, missing functionality, weak boundaries, excessive context, redundant tool use, and token-heavy implementation choices; guide repairs through reproducible feedback; validate correctness at unit and integration levels; and prove that efficiency improvements preserve or improve task quality.

1. INSPECT THE COMPLETE SKILL SURFACE
   - Read repository governance, the target skill, manifests, deterministic triggers, capabilities, routing, scripts, schemas, workflows, tests, known failures, proof vocabulary, generated-output policy, open PRs, and recent commits.
   - Identify every component the skill selects, invokes, reads, writes, or hands off to. Do not evaluate the skill file in isolation when the real behavior spans routing, capability, code, and workflow surfaces.

2. DEFINE THE EVAL CONTRACT BEFORE REPAIR
   For every case record:
   - case ID and version;
   - purpose and weakness class;
   - input and preconditions;
   - expected trigger and route;
   - expected capability calls, artifacts, response properties, and proof level;
   - forbidden outcomes;
   - deterministic assertion or explicit scored rubric;
   - latency, tool-call, context, and token budgets when measurable;
   - completion gate and proof ceiling.

3. BUILD A COMPLETE CASE MATRIX
   Include:
   - positive activation cases;
   - negative and near-miss routing cases;
   - boundary and overlap cases against neighboring skills;
   - malformed-input and missing-precondition cases;
   - forbidden-condition and safe-refusal cases;
   - historical regression cases from real defects;
   - unit tests for deterministic helpers, schemas, triggers, and capability contracts;
   - integration tests across skill + trigger + capability + workflow + artifact;
   - end-to-end or provider-backed cases only in a separately labeled lane with honest cost, authentication, and runtime blockers.

4. IDENTIFY WEAKNESSES, NOT JUST FAILURES
   The eval must detect and classify:
   - functional bugs and incorrect outputs;
   - missing functionality or unhandled conditions;
   - false-positive and false-negative skill selection;
   - ambiguous ownership or overlapping triggers;
   - brittle assumptions and unreproducible behavior;
   - repeated instructions, duplicated context, unnecessary files, redundant tool calls, and avoidable model turns;
   - excessive prompt, completion, or total token use;
   - latency, cost, memory, or artifact-size regressions;
   - proof inflation, unsafe fallback behavior, and hidden application logic in prose.

5. ESTABLISH A REPRODUCIBLE BASELINE
   Before optimization, capture the current:
   - pass/fail and scored-quality results;
   - routing precision and recall where applicable;
   - unit, integration, and regression coverage;
   - latency distribution;
   - tool and model call counts;
   - prompt, completion, cached, and total token usage when available;
   - context files/bytes loaded;
   - cost and failure/retry rate;
   - produced artifacts and proof ceiling.
   Do not claim improvement without a comparable baseline and stable fixture set.

6. USE FEEDBACK-DRIVEN REPAIR
   - Reproduce each valid weakness with a failing case before changing behavior when feasible.
   - Apply test-driven development: add or strengthen the failing eval, make the smallest correct repair, then rerun focused and regression suites.
   - Use profiling or execution traces for performance and token defects rather than guessing.
   - Keep a finding-to-repair ledger linking each defect to evidence, changed files, validating cases, and disposition.
   - Never weaken an assertion, threshold, fixture, or quality rubric merely to make the suite green.

7. OPTIMIZE WITH SOUND FACTORING PRINCIPLES
   Reduce token use and execution waste without hiding behavior or lowering quality:
   - keep each skill bounded to one coherent activation and outcome;
   - split mixed domains, unrelated triggers, or oversized context requirements;
   - merge only materially identical routes and procedures;
   - move deterministic work into code, schemas, registries, validators, and workflows;
   - load only the skill instructions and repository context required for the selected task;
   - replace repeated prose with canonical references or machine-readable contracts;
   - remove duplicate calls, unnecessary intermediate summaries, and repeated repository scans;
   - prefer reusable capabilities over re-explaining operations in every prompt;
   - preserve clarity, safety, correctness, and debuggability while reducing token and latency budgets.

8. PROVE OPTIMIZATION DID NOT DEGRADE QUALITY
   Compare baseline and candidate results on the same versioned cases. A performance or token change passes only when:
   - required correctness and safety gates remain green;
   - no critical regression is introduced;
   - routing quality is preserved or improved;
   - artifact and proof contracts remain satisfied;
   - token, latency, call-count, or cost improvement is measured rather than asserted.
   Report regressions and tradeoffs honestly; do not optimize a proxy while degrading the real task.

9. PRODUCE MACHINE-READABLE RESULTS
   The runner must emit case IDs, versions, target implementation SHA, pass/fail or score, rule and weakness IDs, evidence, timing, call counts, token metrics when available, baseline/candidate deltas, evaluator metadata, artifacts, and proof ceiling. Deterministic failures must return nonzero and block focused CI.

10. VALIDATE AND DELIVER
   - Run the complete focused eval matrix.
   - Run target unit and integration tests, repository validators, build/static checks, secret and generated-output hygiene, and git diff --check.
   - Repair valid failures within owned scope.
   - Commit the coherent eval and skill repair.
   - Push normally and open or update the intended PR when authorized.

FINAL REPORT
Repo, branch, target skill and related capability/trigger surfaces, weakness inventory, case matrix, runner and schema paths, unit/integration/regression results, baseline and candidate performance/token metrics, finding-to-repair ledger, changed files, commit SHA, push or PR state, proof achieved, proof ceiling, final Git status, and one exact next command that runs the eval and opens or prints its canonical result artifact.
